     My question/statement is simple.  Even if we get a huge increase to damage.  Lets keep it simple and put it at 10% increase.  Which in and of itself would be huge.  How is this going to transition the Wizard into being a better group participant?  This would definately be more conductive to a solo environment, but still would keep us low man on the totem pole for group play.  This is of course during your typical EQ day and not including raid situations.<br>
     I feel that when considering caster balance VI and the players need to look at inter caster balance and not just between casters and melee.  Druids, shamans both rock at soloing, and they both rock in a group.  Clerics and enchanters are the ultimate grouping class.  Mages and Necros are both supreme solo classes and can contribute significantly to group play by always providing damage even when out of mana and having some group friendly spells.  Then we have the wizard who is only as good as there mana.  We contribute nothing other than damage in short bursts which can be rivaled by a well equiped melee.  We provide nothing in group buffs or group friendly abilities other than being able to gate.  <br>
<br>
   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uarmok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Armok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Need a log parsed?</span><br>  Posts: 850<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/15/02 2:38 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Real Caster Balance</span><hr size=1> Wizard damage contribution in a conventional group is a function of four factors:<br>
1) spell efficiency (damage/mana)<br>
2) mana regeneration rate<br>
3) combat uptime (itself a function of pull rate and kill time)<br>
4) right click damage (if applicable)<br>
<br>
Combat uptime is an important factor to consider because the lower the combat uptime, the better mana classes will do (because they can &quot;store up&quot; damage by recovering mana) and the worse melee classes do (because they can only do damage while there is something to hit). Regardless of what balancing chages are made, there will be some uptime at which wizard damage output will equal a melee class. Prior to focus items, wizards and monks at level 51 would have equal damage output with about 33% uptime. If the pull rate was higher, monks would do better, while if the pull rate was lower, wizards would do better.<br>
<br>
The point of all the above is that you can make balancing changes (probably increasing wizard damage output, probably through focus items) that put wizard and melee damage contribution in parity for uptime values commonly experienced by conventional groups. As long as our damage contribution potential is at approximately the same level as a melee class, there are good reasons to pick a wizard for a damage dealing group slot when one is available.<br>
<br>
... and if the changes targetted DDs instead of all spells, wizard solo efficiency would not change much. But given how many melee classes can now solo (or duo) very effectively with the right equipment, balancing grouping gains against soloing gains is really a non-issue.<br>
<br>
My bottom line recommentation after doing extensive analysis was the following:<br>
1) add/improve some right click wizard nukes<br>
2) reduce DD mana cost by 25%.<br>
Pretty simple changes, really, but would have given us much better balance in 40% uptime groups without increasing our max DPS (thus leaving our raid contribution about the same as it is now) and without increasing solo capability by much (because AoE spells would be left unchanged). <p>"Evacuate? In our moment of triumph? I think you overestimate their chances!"<BR>
Armok Komra (Triton)<BR>
Sorcerer Emeritus of Povar</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/29/02 2:19 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Amork forgot</span><hr size=1> Amork forgot to mention the advantages of the right-click nuke route.<br>
<br>
It improves wizards more in the high-uptime groups, and less in the low-uptime groups, thus helping wizards where they hurt, and not helping as much where they excell.<br>
<br>
It also is another way to have equipment matter.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utargonis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 594<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/29/02 6:13 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Amork forgot</span><hr size=1> You also forgot ultra-fast casting spells being needed.  In many high uptime groups, mobs drop QUICK.  Dropping one big nuke, or two mediums is nice and all, but it would be nice to have some 2 second cast time nukes, or even a 1 second cast time spell to kill runners.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 60 Wizard<br>
The First Seal<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 5226<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/30/02 9:32 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> the answers</span><hr size=1> Armok's examinations were good but his conclusions were pretty sorry.  What limits a Wizard in an xp group now?<br>
<br>
1) Time, creatures die faster than ever and the Wizard's 'make em die fast' contribution is more meaningless.  Things die so fast at levels past 33 that the new blasts are too slow to come into play very much.<br>
2) Mana, to be a consistant contributer, the Wizard has to either not blast very much or blast a lot and sit even more doing nothing - neither is very helpful to a group.<br>
3) Aggro, nuke too much, get turned into a punching bag, we all know this one.<br>
4) Resistances, hit a monster and do almost nothing - but aggro and use just as much mana.<br>
<br>
Now, if you will note if you peek into the Huge thread Armok started when he did his discussion of what's wrong and how he thought things should be fixed, there is a familiar name posting early on: Gallenite.  Guess who that is?  Its Scott, our buddy in charge of casters right now.  Not too awful long after that came out focus items landed on mages, with exactly the effects I listed above being addressed.<br>
<br>
If you link this to the coming Everquest 2, you'll see a pattern: test things on this EQ to see how they work out in EQ 2.<br>
<br>
The only problem with how they did it is that ALL casters get the same benefits, a Cleric wearing a Naki's Bracer does more damage than a Wizard without one in some level ranges... something I'd find acceptible for a Magician or Druid, but not a Cleric (shouldn't have had nukes in the first place, but that's another discussion).  As such, Wizards aren't really helped all that much by the items specifically, just casters as a whole.  That means Wizards still have a problem, especially if there's no mage around. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uarmok.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Armok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Need a log parsed?</span><br>  Posts: 861<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/30/02 3:33 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: the answers</span><hr size=1> Grim,<br>
<br>
I know that you are not a fan of right click nukes. I do understand your objections (a wizard's power should come from his nukes, not his tools, etc), but when I used figures in my spreadsheet that would balance us without right click nukes, level 60 Wizards got insanely powerful when the Rend Robe is taken into account (outstripping rogues by a fair margin in damage over time in most situations). This means that in order to maintain balance, Verant must aim low with their adjustments (this is what we are seeing so far, imo). This also has the effect of sharpening the power curve for wizards, perpetuating the current situation of very poor relative performance at lower levels, and finally catching up at the end-game.<br>
<br>
Since we won't be able to abolish right click nukes, I decided to embrace them as a part of the solution. Spreading access to these items to lower levels would help to soften the power curve, and would also allow for the problem of melee twinking to be countered with a bit of wizard twinking. They also have the characteristic of being most useful in conventional experience groups and extremely long boss mob fights (where we have tradtionally had problems).<br>
<br>
As for the issue of caster-vs-caster balance: I did not focus my research on this issue. There are most definitely balance problems here as well, but that is a whole 'nother ball o' wax. Interestingly enough, wizard issues are mostly in the pre-60 leveling game, while most of the other caster issues are in the 60+ raid game. As such, applying blanket solutions (such as mage summoned focus items) has the effect of boosting wizards in the raid game and other casters in the leveling game as well as a bit of help in areas where help is needed.<br>
<br>
This is probably a good point to blow my own horn a bit and note that my suggested changes (reducing mana cost for DDs and adding right click nukes at lower levels) would have done very little to boost wizard damage output on raids, which has been at the core of the &quot;nerf wizards&quot; cries of late. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 5229<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/30/02 6:25 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: the answers</span><hr size=1> I'm fine with the idea of adding some right click nukes in, its a classic part of Wizard lore (wands to blast things with when your spells are too slow).  My problem isn't with the concept of the things, its Verant's track record on it.  They COULD do it well, with rechargable items that have a slow recast time and reasonably fast casting time - but their item system doesn't support that right now.  They won't be working on that, its not worth their time and effort.  Adding in a wand that takes 15 seconds to cast an 80 point blast at level 34 is just not going to do the trick, and you know damn well we wouldn't get better than that - and not unless it was a rare drop off a rare spawn in a dungeon well over level 34.<br>
<br>
Its not so much the items, its the likely implementation of them.  Wizards SHOULD have right click blast things, in addition to their normal abilities.  They just shouldn't be the ones Verant has in the game, nor what they'd add in.  Your work got us notice and they did use some ideas I had (the 'why wizards do well on raids' thread was of particular interest to the Verant guys).  The problem is, they did it wholesale, on all casters.  EACH CASTER needs work specific to them, and pretending that adding focus items to all casters helps Wizards is only vaguely right.<br>
<br>
The thing is, as I pointed out above, they are working on EQ2 now and any changes they make are to test that out entirely - so I hope they give us lots of clicky stuff to play with for what its worth now.  I just am opposed to your solutions on how they'll work out in the game, but it is entirely an intellectual exercise. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/utargonis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 600<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/1/02 10:38 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: the answers</span><hr size=1> There's still the issue of how we start weak and end balanced that I find rather stupid and in need of adjustment.  If we start as one of the weakest, and stay the weakest for the longest time, then why don't we get balanced at 50, and get VASTLY more powerful than all other classes by the time we hit 60?  There should be no time past 49 that we are weaker in any sense of the word than any other class because we were weak for so long compared to all other classes.  If people want us to be &quot;balanced&quot; at 60, then at every level, from 1 to 60, we should be dishing out as much damage as ANY other class, and leveling just as easily.  It shouldn't be a struggle for us at all if they don't want us to be more powerful than the other classes at the end game.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 60 Wizard<br>
The First Seal<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugoladus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 1901<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/2/02 12:10 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Real Caster Balance</span><hr size=1> I have yet to see any convicing argument for this widely accepted &quot;start weak and end balanced&quot; theory that didn't depend on twinking.  Everyone just seems to accept it as true.  What if everyone is wrong and it's just a massively overpowering jump in power when you hit 60?<br>
<br>
I get quoted spell numbers and such then have people telling me that their wizards are soloing mobs on 2 bubs of mana at level 25.  /boggle when I was 25 as a mage I remember spending tons more than 2 bubs of mana soloing stuff in loio. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uznailvh.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Znail vh</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 151<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/2/02 7:11 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Real Caster Balance</span><hr size=1> Goladus, all you have to do to see how it is at 25 is to check the spell lists. The spells at that level is very mana innefficient. You will need decent int to be able to kill blue mobs on a full mana bar. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uznailvh.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Znail vh</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 152<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/2/02 7:13 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Real Caster Balance</span><hr size=1> Goladus, all you have to do to see how it is at 25 is to check the spell lists. The spells at that level is very mana innefficient. You will need decent int to be able to kill blue mobs on a full mana bar.<br>
<br>
Opps, almost forgot. At that level so is all you got as defence root. It is often resisted and breaks often as well. This adds to the difficulty. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ufraethir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fraethir</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 123<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/3/02 12:28 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Real Caster Balance</span><hr size=1> Garrison's lowbie love spell helped the 24ish casters quite a lot. Rather doubt they're hunting LoIO and killing things in two bubbles (not bars) of mana. They might be killing dark blue aviaks (or some other old world mob) in two blue, but they're not root/nuking. They might be doing full speed kiting, it's hard to say (a lot of braggarts like that carefully neglect to mention they've got jboots, solist's wand, and KEI up).<br>
<br>
Just some thoughts.<br>
And yes, we might achieve relative balance at L60, but it's a hell of a long slog to get there. And being balanced at the end is never a reason to be weak/imbalanced before then. <br>
<br>
